# Why is Security Important?

Imagine you upload your blood report.

It contains:

```text
Name: Srujan

Age: 35

Blood Group: B+

HbA1c: 6.8

Vitamin D: 18
```

This is personal health information.

Only **you** should be able to see it.

---

# Security Principle #1

## Every user sees only their own reports

Example:

```text
Alice

↓

Alice's Reports Only
```

```text
Bob

↓

Bob's Reports Only
```

Alice should never be able to see Bob's reports.

---

# Security Principle #2

## Secure Login

Users must log in using:

* Email
* Password

Later we can support:

* Google Login
* Apple Login

Without logging in, users should not be able to access reports.

---

# Security Principle #3

## Strong Passwords

Examples:

❌ Bad Password

```text
123456
```

❌ Bad Password

```text
password
```

✅ Better Password

```text
Srujan@2026
```

The app should encourage users to choose stronger passwords.

---

# Security Principle #4

## Passwords Are Never Stored as Plain Text

Suppose the user enters:

```text
MyPassword123
```

We should **never** save:

```text
MyPassword123
```

Instead, the password is transformed into a secure value (called a hash) before being stored.

Even if someone gained access to the database, they should not be able to read users' passwords.

---

# Security Principle #5

## Secure File Storage

Uploaded PDFs should be stored securely.

Instead of:

```text
My Documents

↓

bloodreport.pdf
```

They should be stored in protected cloud storage where only authorized users can access them.

---

# Security Principle #6

## Secure Communication

When the app talks to the server:

```text
Flutter

↓

Backend
```

the communication should be encrypted using HTTPS.

This helps protect information while it travels across the internet.

---

# Security Principle #7

## User Control

Users should be able to:

* View their reports
* Download their reports
* Delete their reports (if supported)
* Delete their account (future feature)

Users should stay in control of their own data.

---

# Security Principle #8

## AI Privacy

When we send blood values to AI:

Example:

```text
Hemoglobin: 11.2

HbA1c: 6.8
```

We should avoid sending unnecessary personal information whenever possible.

For example, AI usually does **not** need:

* Email address
* Phone number
* Home address

It only needs the information required to explain the report.

---

# Security Checklist

Before launching Version 1, our app should have:

✅ User login

✅ Secure passwords

✅ HTTPS communication

✅ Protected cloud storage

✅ Private user accounts

✅ Safe AI usage

---

# What Happens When a User Uploads a Report?

```text
User

↓

Login

↓

Upload PDF

↓

Encrypted Transfer

↓

Secure Cloud Storage

↓

OCR

↓

AI

↓

Database

↓

Only that User Can View It
```

This is the secure flow we want.

---

# Future Security Features

In Version 2 or later, we can add:

* Two-factor authentication (2FA)
* Biometric login (Fingerprint / Face ID)
* Login notifications
* Session management (log out from all devices)
* Automatic logout after inactivity
* Encryption of sensitive data at rest

These aren't essential for the MVP, but they make the app even more secure.

